\chapter*{Abstract}

In this thesis we propose a specification for a module system for the HOL family of theorem provers. We implement the specification for Candle, a verified ITP, and begin to prove its correctness. The module system is written as the introduction of three new inference rules afforded by the system, and the proof of correctness aims to show that these rules are conservative; that is, everything previously derivable remains derivable, and we do not allow anything new to be derived that was not previously. The final proof is not yet complete, but a large library of lemmas shows that the final result is promising, although as of now remains conjecture. Other projects for other theorem provers have presented module systems and theoretical proofs for their correctness, but to the best of the author's knowledge this is the first to attempt their mechanised verification and implementation into a verified theorem prover. The significance of this lies in the trust that the written proofs hold over the specification. The proposed specification represents a ``version 1'' of the final system. What we describe is a restrictive version of an ideal module system, and cannot handle introducing polymorphic types to, for example, instantiate theorems about monoids as ones over polymorphic lists. We discuss how these limitations could be remedied, and how the current incomplete library of proofs could be extended and completed.

\textbf{Keywords:} formal methods, interactive theorem proving, higher-order logic, theory interpretation, prover soundness 
